***************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************

Where flows run

Flows appear at four distinct points, and conflating them causes real confusion:

Before-save record-triggered flow → step 3. Runs before your before triggers, in the same save transaction, no separate DML. This is the fastest automation Salesforce offers for simple same-record field updates — roughly 10× faster than a workflow field update because there's no second save. Consequence: if a flow and a trigger both set the same field, the flow writes first and the trigger overwrites it.

After-save record-triggered flow → step 16. Runs after escalation rules. Can create/update related records, send emails, call Apex. Any DML it performs kicks off a fresh order of execution on the target object.

Processes and flows launched from workflow rules → step 14. Legacy path. Immediate actions only.

Scheduled and async paths of record-triggered flows → step 22 / later. Scheduled paths run after commit at their configured time, in a separate transaction with fresh governor limits. Async paths (used for callouts) run post-commit. Neither is inside your transaction, so neither can roll it back.

Screen flows are not in this list at all — they're user-driven UI, not DML-triggered. But each DML the screen flow executes runs the full order of execution for that object.

*******************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************************
Where validation rules fire

Step 5 — after before triggers, before the save. Two implications that matter:

Before triggers can fix or break validation. If a before trigger populates a required field, the validation rule at step 5 sees the populated value and passes. Conversely, a before trigger blanking a field will trip a validation rule the user never touched, and the error message will confuse them.

They do not re-run after workflow field updates. Step 13 re-fires update triggers but explicitly skips custom validation rules, duplicate rules, and escalation rules. So a workflow field update can write a value that violates a validation rule and it goes through. Same for the roll-up path — actually no, step 18 is the opposite case and worth calling out separately below.

Apex addError() is effectively validation at step 4 — one step earlier than declarative rules. If both would fire, the user sees your Apex message first because the save aborts before step 5.

Validation rules run on API/Apex DML. Only the layout-specific system validation at step 2 is skipped for non-UI saves. Custom validation rules always apply — which is why a bulk data load can fail on rules the admin forgot about.

The roll-up trap at step 18: when a child update recalculates a parent roll-up, the parent runs its entire save procedure including its own validation rules. If the new roll-up value violates a validation rule on the parent, the parent's save fails, and because it's all one transaction, the child's save fails too. Users get an error about a record they didn't edit.
