The static boolean — and why it's usually wrong
apex
public class TriggerGuard {
    public static Boolean hasRun = false;
}
apex
trigger AccountTrigger on Account (after update) {
    if (TriggerGuard.hasRun) return;
    TriggerGuard.hasRun = true;
    AccountTriggerHandler.doWork(Trigger.new, Trigger.oldMap);
}

Statics live for the duration of the execution context, so this does stop re-entry. It also has a serious bug:

DML on more than 200 records fires the trigger in chunks of 200. Update 500 Accounts and the trigger runs three times as separate legitimate invocations. The first chunk sets hasRun = true; chunks 2 and 3 silently skip. You process 200 records and drop 300. This bug survives every test that inserts fewer than 201 records — which is most tests.

(Related trap for Batch Apex: statics reset between each execute() call. Database.Stateful preserves instance variables, not statics. So a guard behaves differently in batch than in a single transaction.)
