Better: track which records you've processed

public class TriggerGuard {
    private static Set<Id> processedIds = new Set<Id>();

    public static Set<Id> getUnprocessed(Set<Id> candidateIds) {
        Set<Id> fresh = new Set<Id>(candidateIds);
        fresh.removeAll(processedIds);
        processedIds.addAll(fresh);
        return fresh;
    }
}

public static void doWork(List<Account> newAccts, Map<Id, Account> oldMap) {

    Set<Id> toProcess = TriggerGuard.getUnprocessed(oldMap.keySet());
    if (toProcess.isEmpty()) return;

    for (Account a : newAccts) {
        if (!toProcess.contains(a.Id)) continue;
        // ...
    }
}

Record-scoped rather than transaction-scoped, so chunk 2 of a 500-record update proceeds normally while genuine re-entry on the same record is blocked.

