Practical checklist
* Recursion protection lives in the handler, not the trigger — it should be testable independently
* If you must use a static flag, reset it appropriately or use the Set<Id> variant; never a bare boolean on an object that gets bulk-loaded
* If you're calling update in an after update trigger on the same object, first ask whether that logic belongs in before update — that usually removes the recursion entirely
* Test with 201+ records specifically to catch the chunking bug

Natural next stops from here: the trigger handler framework (fflib or a lightweight base class), @TestSetup and bulk test patterns, and asynchronous Apex — Queueable vs @future vs Batch — which is where step 22 gets interesting.

